Statistics_Lecture1

Collected data

byuHair <- c(0.54, 0.75, 2.45, 4.23, 0.00, 1.21, 1.98, 5.54, 0.15, 2.67, 0.00, 1.98, 1.34, 4.31, 2.22, 0.99)
utahHair <- c( 1.11, 10.5, 4.06, 7.92, 0.21, 1.54, 0.00, 0.25, 2.95, 5.42, 0.55, 3.88, 15.2, 1.33, 1.44, 6.65)

Plot histograms

hist(byuHair, main="BYU", xlab="Hair length (inches)", xlim=c(0, max(byuHair, utahHair)), breaks=16)

hist(utahHair, main="U. of Utah", xlab="Hair length (inches)", xlim=c(0, max(byuHair, utahHair) + 1), breaks=16)

Plot boxplot

boxplot(cbind(byuHair, utahHair), col=c("blue", "red"), names=c("BYU", "Utah"), range=0)

Assess normality of data

qqnorm(byuHair, main="BYU")
qqline(byuHair)

qqnorm(utahHair, main="Utah")
qqline(utahHair)

Perform (two-sample, unpaired) t-test

t.test(byuHair, utahHair)
##

Perform (two-sample, unpaired) Wilcoxon rank-sum test

# This test is like a t-test, but it compares the ranks of the values rather than the actual values
wilcox.test(byuHair, utahHair)
## Warning in wilcox.test.default(byuHair, utahHair): cannot compute exact p-
## value with ties
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  byuHair and utahHair
## W = 98, p-value = 0.266
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0

Calculate a bootstrap estimate of the mean

# Set random seed
set.seed(1)

# Initialize bootstrap value vector
bootstrapMeans <- NULL

# Iterate 1000 times
for (i in 1:1000)
{
  # Sample with replacement
  newSample <- sample(byuHair, replace=TRUE)
  
  # Calculate mean of bootstrapped sample and append it to vector
  bootstrapMeans <- c(bootstrapMeans, mean(newSample))
}

# Plot histogram of bootstrap values
hist(bootstrapMeans, main="BYU - Bootstrap Means", xlab="Hair length (inches)")

# Add vertical line to plot
abline(v=mean(byuHair), col="blue", lty=2, lwd=2)

# Set random seed
set.seed(1)

# Initialize bootstrap value vector
bootstrapMeans <- NULL

# Iterate 1000 times
for (i in 1:1000)
{
  # Sample with replacement
  newSample <- sample(utahHair, replace=TRUE)
  
  # Calculate mean of bootstrapped sample and append it to vector
  bootstrapMeans <- c(bootstrapMeans, mean(newSample))
}

# Plot histogram of bootstrap values
hist(bootstrapMeans, main="U. of Utah - Bootstrap Means", xlab="Hair length (inches)")

# Add vertical lines
abline(v=mean(utahHair), col="red", lty=2, lwd=2)
abline(v=mean(byuHair), col="blue", lty=2, lwd=2)

One-way ANOVA example

uvuHair <- c(0.22, 5.45, 1.11, 1.99, 12.4, 11.9, 3.33, 2.22, 8.88, 4.44, 0.88, 0.00, 2.55, 5.23, 3.09, 9.05)

# Build a data frame that contains data from all three schools
hairData <- as.data.frame(rbind(cbind("BYU", byuHair), cbind("Utah", utahHair), cbind("UVU", uvuHair)))
colnames(hairData) <- c("School", "HairLength")

# Make sure the data types are correct
hairData$School <- as.factor(hairData$School)
hairData$HairLength <- as.numeric(hairData$HairLength)

# Create box plot
boxplot(HairLength ~ School, data=hairData, range=0, col=c("blue", "red", "darkgreen"))

# Fit an ANOVA model to the goal.
# The goal of ANOVA is to understand whether the mean values are different across the groups
anovaFit <- aov(HairLength ~ School, data=hairData)
summary(anovaFit)
##             Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)
## School       2    408   203.8   1.303  0.282
## Residuals   45   7039   156.4
# Tukey's Honestly Significant Difference test can be used to assess statistical significance when comparing each group pair
TukeyHSD(anovaFit)
##   Tukey multiple comparisons of means
##     95% family-wise confidence level
## 
## Fit: aov(formula = HairLength ~ School, data = hairData)
## 
## $School
